Based on response.md, all three components are called from the Client (per-exchange orchestrator), not directly from the server or directly visible to the client (browser). Here's the breakdown:

Who calls what
The orchestrator is Client — see response.md:151-167:

Component	Called by	When
RequestHandler::handle()	Client::onReceive()	After parser reports the request is complete
RequestHandler::handleError()	Client::onReceive()	When the parser reports an error
HttpResponseWriter::serialize()	Client::onReceive()	Right after the handler populates the response
HttpResponse (writers)	RequestHandler	Inside handle() / handleError() to fill status/headers/body
HttpResponse (readers)	HttpResponseWriter	While serializing into the write buffer
HttpResponse::clear()	Client::onResponseSent()	Per-exchange reset on keep-alive
The chain of responsibility
response.md:184-186 makes the rule explicit:

Client is the orchestrator, but it contains no HTTP rule logic of its own. Every HTTP decision goes through one of parser_, handler_, or HttpResponseWriter.

So the answer to "client or server":

Server-side Client (the per-connection object in your reactor) — drives the calls.
Reactor never touches these — it only sees responseData()/shouldClose() and does the actual send() (response.md:190-192).
The browser/HTTP client is not involved at all — it just receives the bytes the writer produced.
Ownership recap from response.md:24-25: HttpResponse is owned by Client, populated by RequestHandler, read by HttpResponseWriter.

